espionage.”

93
00:04:01,569 --> 00:04:04,459
Simply put, officials are worried that Huawei

94
00:04:04,459 --> 00:04:07,430
will help the Chinese regime spy on the US

95
00:04:07,430 --> 00:04:10,000
or attack America’s cyber infrastructure.

96
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:12,690
How might Huawei do that specifically?

97
00:04:12,690 --> 00:04:14,880
One way is “that companies like Huawei

98
00:04:14,880 --> 00:04:18,329
might sell products compromised by ‘back
doors’

99
00:04:18,329 --> 00:04:20,069
that allow Chinese government hackers

100
00:04:20,069 --> 00:04:22,210
access to data or surveillance."

101
00:04:22,210 --> 00:04:23,210
Although frankly,

102
00:04:23,210 --> 00:04:25,500
I’m more concerned that if we put all our
technology

103
00:04:25,500 --> 00:04:28,590
in the hands of equipment made in China,

104
00:04:28,590 --> 00:04:30,680
one day it will simply stop working.

105
00:04:30,680 --> 00:04:32,290
And when we try to reach customer service,

106
00:04:32,290 --> 00:04:34,840
we keep getting redirected to the Chinese
consulate.

107
00:04:34,840 --> 00:04:37,110
And they don’t even have our package!

108
00:04:37,110 --> 00:04:40,069
Now, back in 2011 and 2012,

109
00:04:40,069 --> 00:04:43,960
Vodaphone did find hidden backdoors in Huawei
equipment.

110
00:04:43,960 --> 00:04:46,979
And there have been other reports of Huawei
backdoors.

111
00:04:46,979 --> 00:04:48,740
But it’s not clear whether Huawei

112
00:04:48,740 --> 00:04:50,879
purposefully included these backdoors,

113
00:04:50,879 --> 00:04:53,129
or whether they were accidental security flaws

114
00:04:53,129 --> 00:04:55,680
resulting from bad design.

115
00:04:55,680 --> 00:04:57,689
Either way is bad.

116
00:04:57,689 --> 00:05:00,270
So is there smoking gun evidence that Huawei

117
00:05:00,270 --> 00:05:02,939
is putting back doors into its technology,

118
00:05:02,939 --> 00:05:05,629
designed to allow it to spy on users?

119
00:05:05,629 --> 00:05:06,629
No.

120
00:05:06,629 --> 00:05:08,850
But there’s plenty of reason to believe

121
00:05:08,850 --> 00:05:11,229
they would be motivated to.

122
00:05:11,229 --> 00:05:13,669
Like Huawei's uncomfortably close links

123
00:05:13,669 --> 00:05:16,419
to the armed wing of the Chinese Communist
Party—

124
00:05:16,419 --> 00:05:18,409
the People's Liberation Army.

125
00:05:18,409 --> 00:05:21,360
"Huawei is the PLA.

126
00:05:21,360 --> 00:05:26,669
And if the senior executives of Huawei don't
like me saying that,

127
00:05:26,669 --> 00:05:28,310
then bring it.

128
00:05:28,310 --> 00:05:32,229
You are—and I would love to have discovery
on this one—

129
00:05:32,229 --> 00:05:34,050
you are the People's Liberation Army."

130
00:05:34,050 --> 00:05:36,150
I know what you’re thinking.

131
00:05:36,150 --> 00:05:38,589
Steve Bannon, he’s probably just trying
to rile people up

132
00:05:38,589 --> 00:05:41,199
by mispronouncing Wah-Wey

133
00:05:41,199 --> 00:05:42,910
and mentioning the PLA.

134
00:05:42,910 --> 00:05:44,190
It turns out, no.

135
00:05:44,190 --> 00:05:47,050
Bannon just doesn’t know how to pronounce
Huawei, either.

136
00:05:47,050 --> 00:05:50,919
Also, the founder and CEO of Huawei, Ren Zhengfei,

137
00:05:50,919 --> 00:05:53,569
was an engineer with the People's Liberation
Army.

138
00:05:53,569 --> 00:05:55,990
And last year for the 40th anniversary of
China’s

139
00:05:55,990 --> 00:05:58,090
so-called “reform and opening-up,”

140
00:05:58,090 --> 00:06:02,520
Ren Zhengfei was hailed one of 100 “excellent
private entrepreneurs”

141
00:06:02,520 --> 00:06:06,740
who “firmly safeguard the leadership of
the Chinese Communist party.”

142
00:06:06,740 --> 00:06:10,249
So much for being a totally independent private
company.

143
00:06:10,249 --> 00:06:14,809
But the Trump administration’s moves have
already hamstrung Huawei.

144
00:06:14,809 --> 00:06:19,169
For now, the Commerce Department’s Entity
List has had the biggest effect.

145
00:06:19,169 --> 00:06:22,940
That’s the one that prevents US companies
from selling to Huawei.

146
00:06:22,940 --> 00:06:24,089
According to Bloomberg,

147
00:06:24,089 --> 00:06:27,219
top US tech companies have already begun to
cut off

148
00:06:27,219 --> 00:06:31,279
the supply of microchips and other technology
to Huawei.

149
00:06:31,279 --> 00:06:33,369
Chinese state-run media has gone on the defensive,

150
00:06:33,369 --> 00:06:35,069
saying the Huawei ban is nothing

151
00:06:35,069 --> 00:06:39,199
and we’ll be totally fine without chips
from American suppliers,

152
00:06:39,199 --> 00:06:42,780
and really, who wants Made in America chips
anyway?

153
00:06:42,780 --> 00:06:46,210
Huawei's chip arm HiSilicon said last Friday

154
00:06:46,210 --> 00:06:47,740
it's been prepared for the scenario

155
00:06:47,740 --> 00:06:51,240
that it could be banned from purchasing U.S.
chips and technology.

156
00:06:51,240 --> 00:06:54,009
HiSilicon says it's been "vigorously investing

157
00:06:54,009 --> 00:06:56,090
in self-developed technologies,

158
00:06:56,090 --> 00:06:58,919
and is able to ensure a steady supply of most
products

159
00:06:58,919 --> 00:07:02,240
to make sure Huawei will be able to continue
serving its customers."

160
00:07:02,240 --> 00:07:06,379
Or, as HiSilicon president said in a letter
cited by Straits Times,

161
00:07:06,379 --> 00:07:11,139
“now is the time for ‘all the spare tyres
in the safe’ to become useful.”

162
